PickKeysByValue

PickKeysByValue<Target, ValueType>: { [ Key in keyof Target]-?: Target[Key] extends ValueType ? Key : never }[keyof Target]
  • Defined in src/ts/@types/object.ts:442

PickKeysByValue

example
  interface Temp { req: number, reqUndef: number | undefined, opt?: string }
  // Expect: 'req'
  type test1 = PickKeysByValue<Temp, number>
  // Expect: 'req' | 'reqUndef'
  type test2 = PickKeysByValue<Temp, number | undefined>
attention

(For ALL ByValue utilities) When we want to get 'opt' as result in above example, PickKeysByValue<Temp, string> will not work. We should use PickKeysByValue<Temp, string | undefined> instead. It's so weird that we don't always know whether the target key is optional or not in actual most of situations so we have to include undefined in the target matching ValueType's union. It's unnecessary and redundant.

       On the other hand, normal keys and optional keys are quite different. We indeed need an approach to
       distinguish them. Seems like add `undefined` to the union of optional keys' value type is a reasonable way.

       Here our final choice is give `undefined` a chance until we get a more fantastic solution. Meanwhile, turn the
       `exactOptionalPropertyTypes: true` typescript's compiler option on. It will make the use of `undefined` on optional
       properties more reasonable. For more information on it: see <a href="https://www.typescriptlang.org/tsconfig#exactOptionalPropertyTypes" class="external">https://www.typescriptlang.org/tsconfig#exactOptionalPropertyTypes</a>,
       there's also a use guide on that information, see <a href="https://tkdodo.eu/blog/optional-vs-undefined" class="external">https://tkdodo.eu/blog/optional-vs-undefined</a>.

Type parameters

  • Target

  • Defined in src/ts/@types/object.ts:602

ObjectOverwrite

description

From U overwrite properties to T.

example
  interface Props { name: string, age: number, visible: boolean }
  interface NewProps { age: string, other: string }

  // Expect: { name: string; age: string; visible: boolean; }
  type ReplacedProps = ObjectOverwrite<Props, NewProps>
see

  • Defined in src/ts/@types/object.ts:619

ObjectAssign

description

From U assign properties to T (just like object assign).

example
  interface Props { name: string, age: number, visible: boolean }
  interface NewProps { age: string, other: string }

  // Expect: { name: string; age: string; visible: boolean; other: string; }
  type ExtendedProps = ObjectAssign<Props, NewProps>

ObjectUnionize

desc

Disjoin object to form union of objects, each with single property.

example
  interface Props { name: string, age: number, visible: boolean }

Brand

Brand<Target, Token>: Token extends StringLiteral<Token> ? Target & { __brand__: Token } : never
  • Defined in src/ts/@types/other.ts:26

Brand

desc

Define nominal type of U based on type of T. Similar to Opaque types in Flow.

example

type USD = Brand<number, "USD"> type EUR = Brand<number, "EUR">

const tax = 5 as USD; const usd = 10 as USD; const eur = 10 as EUR;

function gross(net: USD): USD { return (net + tax) as USD; }

// Expect: No compile error gross(usd); // Expect: Compile error (Type '"EUR"' is not assignable to type '"USD"'.) gross(eur);

see

Copyright - The code is copy from https://github.com/piotrwitek/utility-types/blob/master/src/mapped-types.ts , mixed with https://github.com/ts-essentials/ts-essentials/blob/5aa1f264e77fb36bb3f673c49f00927c7c181a7f/lib/types.ts#L416

see

Alternative - Name it as Type or Opaque, https://millsp.github.io/ts-toolbelt/modules/any_type.html

Type parameters

  • Target

  • Token: string

Vacuo

Vacuo: ((...args: any[]) => Vacuo) & { __type__: "Vacuo" } & Meta
  • Defined in src/ts/atom/metas.ts:110

A value that can serve as the value (for Datar, or transformation for Mutator) of Datar and Mutator at the same time. Base on feature of "JavaScript Function is also an Object", Vacuo can be both Datar's and Mutator's value, says Empty Datar and Empty Mutator respectively.

Content security policy compatible version of Vacuo. The "class Vacuo extends Function" syntax can not use in strict browsers. reference: https://developer.chrome.com/docs/apps/contentSecurityPolicy/

makeDataInArray

  • makeDataInArray<V>(targets: V, options?: BatchMakeOptions & { forceWrap: false }): WrapDataInArray<V>
  • makeDataInArray<V>(targets: V, options?: BatchMakeOptions & { forceWrap: true }): ForceWrapDataInArray<V>
    • Defined in src/ts/atom/helpers/batch-create.helpers.ts:84

    forceWrap - true: items will be wrapped in Data. See {@link forceWrapToData}.

    forceWrap - false: Mutations will be transform to Data, Datas will not be handled, other values will be wrapped in Data. See {@link wrapToData}.

    example
      const tupleA: [number, Data<number>, number] = [1, Data.of(2), 3]
      const arrayA = [1, 2, 3]
      // Expect: [Data<number>, Data<number>, Data<number>]
      const dataInTupleA = makeDataInArray(tupleA)
      // Expect: Data<number>[]
      const dataInArrayA = makeDataInArray(arrayA)

    Type parameters

    • V: readonly any[] = any

    Parameters

    • targets: V
    • Optional options: BatchMakeOptions & { forceWrap: false }

    Returns WrapDataInArray<V>

    • Defined in src/ts/atom/helpers/batch-create.helpers.ts:87

    Type parameters

    • V: readonly any[] = any

    Parameters

    • targets: V
    • Optional options: BatchMakeOptions & { forceWrap: true }

makeDataInObject

  • makeDataInObject<V>(targets: V, options?: BatchMakeOptions & { forceWrap: false }): WrapDataInObject<V>
  • makeDataInObject<V>(targets: V, options?: BatchMakeOptions & { forceWrap: true }): ForceWrapDataInObject<V>
    • Defined in src/ts/atom/helpers/batch-create.helpers.ts:129

    forceWrap - true: items will be wrapped in Data. See {@link forceWrapToData}.

    forceWrap - false: Mutations will be transform to Data, Datas will not be handled, other values will be wrapped in Data. See {@link wrapToData}.

    example

      const namedObject = { a: 1, b: Data.of(2), c: 3 }
      // Expect: { a: Data<number>, b: Data<number>, c: Data<number> }
      const dataInNamedObject = makeDataInObject(namedObject)

Const createFunctionTrigger

  • createFunctionTrigger<P, R>(options: FunctionTriggerCreateOptions<P, R>): Trigger<R>
    • Defined in src/ts/atom/helpers/derive-create.helpers.ts:506
    example
    //                                  slow usecase
    // first create an emit variable which used to hold the real emit function,
    //   we can separately call this function to emit values to our trigger later
    let emit

    // then we create an agent function, which takes an inner emit function as 1st argument,
    //   and internally assign the inner emit function to the emit variable which we created in last step
    const agent = (innerEmit) => {
      emit = innerEmit
    }

    // then create a trigger, specify the agent function
    //   and the handler function which will be called with the arguments passed to emit function later
    //   the return value will be passed to the trigger
    const trigger = createFunctionTrigger({ agent, handler: (score) => score + 1 })

    // call the emit function which hold be the pre-declared variable
    //   the trigger will emit 100 (which equals to `99 + 1`)
    emit(99)

    //                                 quick usecase
    // create all we need using the `createFunctionTriggerAgent` function
    //   only need to specify the handler function
    const agent = createFunctionTriggerAgent((score: number) => score + 1)

    // then pass the created agent to the FunctionTrigger creator using the spread operator
    const const trigger = createFunctionTrigger({ ...agent })

    // call the emit function hold by `agent` to trigger value
    agent.emit(99)

    Type parameters

    • P: any[] = any[]

    • R = any

    Parameters

    • options: FunctionTriggerCreateOptions<P, R>

    Returns Trigger<R>

    • Defined in src/ts/atom/helpers/tween-link.helpers.ts:70

    Automatically pipe two atom

    • if they are in different type, use normal pipe logic
    • if they are in same type, create a tween atom between them, then use normal pipe logic to three atom
      • for Data atom, tween atom is the type of Mutation (asIs Mutation)
      • for Mutation atom, tween atom is the type of Data

    Type parameters

  • caseT<T, V>(preds: StringRecord<Pred<T> | AtomLikeOfOutput<Pred<T>>>, cases: StringRecord<V | AtomLikeOfOutput<V>>, target: AtomLikeOfOutput<T>): Data<V>

    arrayCaseT, objectCaseT

    Type parameters

    • T

    • V

    Parameters

    • preds: (Pred<T> | AtomLikeOfOutput<Pred<T>>)[]

      A bunch of predicates, a predicate is a function that takes a value and returns boolean.

    • cases: (V | AtomLikeOfOutput<V>)[]

      A bunch of cases, each case is corresponding to a predicate, when predicates return true, the corresponding case will be returned as final value.

    • target: AtomLikeOfOutput<T>

      The target's value will be passed to predicates.

    Returns Data<V>

  • defaultToT<V>(dft: V | AtomLikeOfOutput<V>, target: AtomLikeOfOutput<V>): Data<V>
    • Defined in src/ts/atom/taches/defaultTo.taches.ts:24

    Takes a default value and a target atom as argument, emit given default value if value of target atom isVoid.

    • dynamic version: default value must be an Atom.
    • static version: default value can be any type of value.

Const effectT

  • effectT<V, T>(effect: Effect<V, T>, target: AtomLikeOfOutput<T>): Data<V>
    • Defined in src/ts/atom/taches/effect.taches.ts:32

    effectT transfer the value's emittion authority to the effect function, so developer can control whether, when and what value will be emitted.

    see

    dynamicEffectT, staticEffectT

    Type parameters

    • V

    • T

    Parameters

    • effect: Effect<V, T>

      A function that controls the value's emittion. When there is a target value received, the effect function will be invoked. It takes an emit function as first argument, invoke it with the value to emit it. And takes the target value as second argument, an value set function whose value will be emitted just after effect function's execution.

    • target: AtomLikeOfOutput<T>

      Atom

    Returns Data<V>

    Data

    promiseSwitch Tache will emits a "to" value when "from" value comes.

Const pathnameToArray

  • pathnameToArray(pathname: PathnameUnion): PathnameArray
    • Defined in src/ts/external/path.ts:104
    example
    pathnameToArray(['']) 👉 ['', '']
    pathnameToArray(['', '']) 👉 ['', '']
    pathnameToArray(['app', 'page']) 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page' ]
    pathnameToArray(['', 'app', 'page']) 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page']
    pathnameToArray(['', 'app', '', 'page']) 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page']
    pathnameToArray(['', 'app', '', 'page', '']) 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page', '']
    pathnameToArray(['', '', 'app', '', 'page', '']) 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page', '']
    pathnameToArray(['', '', 'app', '', '', 'page', '']) 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page', '']
    pathnameToArray(['', '', 'app', '', '', 'page', '', '']) 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page', '']
    pathnameToArray('app/page') 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page' ]
    pathnameToArray('/app/page') 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page' ]
    pathnameToArray('/app/page/') 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page', '' ]
    pathnameToArray('//app/page/') 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page', '' ]
    pathnameToArray('//app//page/') 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page', '' ]
    pathnameToArray('//app//page//') 👉 [ '', 'app', 'page', '' ]

    Parameters

    • pathname: PathnameUnion

    Returns PathnameArray

Const pathnameToString

  • pathnameToString(pathname: PathnameUnion): string
    • Defined in src/ts/external/path.ts:136
    example
    pathnameToString(['']) // '/'
    pathnameToString(['', '']) // '/'
    pathnameToString(['app', 'page']) // '/app/page'
    pathnameToString(['', 'app', 'page']) // '/app/page'
    pathnameToString(['app', '', 'page']) // '/app/page'
    pathnameToString(['app', 'page', '']) // '/app/page/'
    pathnameToString(['', 'app', '', 'page', '']) // '/app/page/'
    pathnameToString(['', '', 'app', '', '', 'page', '', '']) // '/app/page/'
    pathnameToString('') // '/'
    pathnameToString('/') // '/'
    pathnameToString('//') // '/'
    pathnameToString('/app/page') // '/app/page'
    pathnameToString('//app/page') // '/app/page'
    pathnameToString('//app//page') // '/app/page'
    pathnameToString('//app//page/') // '/app/page/'
    pathnameToString('//app//page//') // '/app/page/'

    Parameters

    • pathname: PathnameUnion

    Returns string

Const isPathnameStrictEqual

  • isPathnameStrictEqual(pathname1: PathnameUnion, pathname2: PathnameUnion): boolean
    • Defined in src/ts/external/path.ts:157

    (strict) judge whether two pathname are equal.

    • strict mode: pathname must be equal
    • loose mode: pathname must be equal despite the last '/'

    '/app/page' equals '/app/page'
    '/app/page' not equals '/app/page/'

    • pathname2: PathnameUnion

Const isGeneralObject

  • isGeneralObject(target: unknown): target is Object
    • Defined in src/ts/internal/base.ts:75

    Predicate whether the targetget is a general object, use typeof operator to check.

    A general object is an object that is:

    • not null, not a function, not a primitive.

    Any other object is a general object:

    • Array instance, Map instance, WeakMap instance, Set instance, Date instance, etc.
    code
    typeof null // => 'object'
    typeof [] // => 'object'
    typeof {} // => 'object'
    typeof { a: 1 } // => 'object'
    typeof (new Map()) // => 'object'
    typeof (new WeakMap()) // => 'object'
    typeof (new Set()) // => 'object'
    typeof (new WeakSet()) // => 'object'
    typeof (new Date()) // => 'object'
    typeof window // => 'object'
    typeof document // => 'object'
    see

    isObject, isPlainObject

    Parameters

    • target: unknown

    Returns target is Object

Const isPlainObject

  • isPlainObject(target: unknown): target is PlainObject
    • Defined in src/ts/internal/base.ts:93

    Predicate whether the targetget is a plain object.

    A plain object is an object that is:

    • not null, not a function, not a primitive type,
    • not an Array, not a RegExp, not a Date, not a Map, not a Set, not a WeakMap,
    • not window, not a DOM element, not an Error,
    • not any other customize object type.
    see

    isObject, isGeneralObject

    Parameters

    • target: unknown

    Returns target is PlainObject

Const isEmpty

  • isEmpty(target: any): boolean
    • Defined in src/ts/internal/base.ts:192
    • null and undefined are considered empty values
    • '' is the empty value for String
    • [] is the empty value for Array
    • {} is the empty value for PlainObject
    • for other object types, they will be considered empty when the value of their isEmpty property is true
    see

    isNull, isUndefined, isEmptyString, isEmptyArray, isEmptyObject

    Parameters

    • target: any

    Returns boolean

    • Defined in src/ts/internal/boolean.ts:195

    Take a function that returns a boolean value, return a complement function that return the opposite boolean value. i.e. whenever target function return true, the complement function will return false, and vice versa.

    Type parameters

    • FN: AnyFunctionOfReturn<boolean>

      The target function's type.

    Parameters

    • fn: FN

      The function returns boolean.

    Returns InvertFunctionReturn<FN>

Const ifElse

  • ifElse<X, TR, ER>(pred: unknown, thenFn: (x?: X) => TR, elseFn: (x?: X) => ER, x?: X): TR | ER
    • Defined in src/ts/internal/boolean.ts:271

    Invoke the conditional function with the target value, according to the predicate result.

    Type parameters

    • X = unknown

    • TR = unknown

      The return type of thenFn.

    • ER = unknown

      The return type of elseFn.

    Parameters

    • pred: unknown

      Value of type any, the value will be converted to boolean using bool function. If pred is of type NormalFunction, it will be invoked with provided x. then the invoke result will be converted to boolean using bool function.

    • thenFn: (x?: X) => TR

      The function to be invoked if pred result is truthy.

        • (x?: X): TR

        • Parameters

          • Optional x: X

          Returns TR

    • elseFn: (x?: X) => ER

      The function to be invoked if pred result is falsy.

        • (x?: X): ER

        • Parameters

          • Optional x: X

          Returns ER

    • Optional x: X

      The target value, which will be pass to pred | thenFn | elseFn.

    Returns TR | ER

  • unless<X, UR>(pred: unknown, unlessFn: (x?: X) => UR, x: X): UR
    • Defined in src/ts/internal/boolean.ts:316

    Invoke the target function with target value, unless the predicate result is truthy.

    Type parameters

    • X = unknown

      The type of the target value.

    • UR = unknown

      The return type of unlessFn.

    Parameters

    • pred: unknown

    • unlessFn: (x?: X) => UR

      The function to be invoked if pred result is falsy. If x is provided, it will be passed to unlessFn.

        • (x?: X): UR

        • Parameters

          • Optional x: X

          Returns UR
